{{About|the Germanic narrative verse genre|the French verse form|Lai (disambiguation){{!}}Lai}}
The '''heroic lay''' is a genre of [[Germanic culture|Germanic]] [[epic poetry]] characteristic of the [[Migration Period]] and the [[Early Middle Ages]]. A lay is a short narrative poem of between 80 and 200 lines concerning a single heroic episode in the life of a warrior from Germanic legend. {{sfn|Hatto|1980|p=165|ps=. "A terse, self-contained, objective, memorized poem of epic-dramatic style imbued with an heroic ethos conveyed with art in a single-stranded plot"}}{{sfn|Gloning|Young|2004|p=42|ps=. "a short poem extolling the valour and nobility of character of a great hero of the past."}} It is distinct from the '''heroic epic''' ([[Beowulf]], [[Nibelungenlied]]) which combines a sequence of episodes into a longer narrative.{{sfn|Heusler|1905}}

